import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    
    dependencies_count = data['source'].value_counts()
    plt.hist(dependencies_count, bins='auto', edgecolor='black')
    
    if len(plt.xticks()[0]) > 20:
        plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MaxNLocator(20))
    
    plt.title("What is the distribution of the number of dependencies per source node?", wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
chart.show()

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    
    # Calculate node degree
    node_degree = data.groupby('source').size().reset_index(name='degree')
    
    # Calculate number of dependencies
    num_dependencies = data.groupby('target').size().reset_index(name='dependencies')
    
    # Merge the two dataframes
    merged_data = pd.merge(node_degree, num_dependencies, left_on='source', right_on='target')
    
    # Create scatter plot
    plt.scatter(merged_data['degree'], merged_data['dependencies'])
    
    # Set title
    plt.title('What is the relationship between the number of dependencies and the node degree?', wrap=True)
    
    # Rotate x axis labels if necessary
    if len(plt.xticks()[0]) > 20:
        plt.xticks(rotation=45)
        plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MaxNLocator(20))
    
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
chart.show()
